l and national context, Lizbet Simmons shows how young black males are in the liminal state of losing educational affiliation while being caught in the net of correctional control. In The Prison School, she asks how schools and prisons became so intertwined. What does this mean for students, communities, and a democratic society? And how do we unravel the ties that bind the racialized realities of school failure and mass incarceration?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfrican American young menxDisciplinexLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aAfrican American young menxEducationxLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aAfrican American young menxEducationzLouisianazNew Orleans. 0aAfrican American young menzLouisianazNew OrleansxDiscipline. 0aJuvenile correctionsxLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aJuvenile correctionszLouisianazNew Orleans. 0aSchool disciplinexLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aSchool disciplinezLouisianazNew Orleans. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520293144423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520293144.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066754-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles